metadata.name: CrossWorlds #171
metadata.description:
In 2057 an error occurred in the particle accelerator machine causing a diversion in space-time that leads to duplication of our world. Scientists discovered that they can travel to these "CrossWorlds" with wormholes plagued by singularities occurring at weakened points of the fabric between worlds. In time, some worlds became hostile to each other, tried to plunder their natural resources, and take over civilizations but other worlds learned how to co-exist peacefully...
------------------
Animation_
Press R: Rotates the world 180¬∞
Idle: Default animation cycles from corner to corner
Mouse: Cursor-dependent animation
MobileDevice: Controls the animation with the orientation of the device. (Android only)
------------------
Live-view_
Resolution: Add "&res=" end of your url with a resolution multiplier. (0.5-6)
Press S: Saves the current scene (Default 1600x1600 px).
Press L: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as PNG.
Press D: Zip file containing all drawing layers separately as SVG.
------------------
Created with p5js.

metadata.name: Ersbla #564
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.

metadata.name: SCHNEEWALD #172
metadata.description:
SCHNEEWALD is the second release in a row of about 12 tree/flower generative art works, which have come together over the last 10 years.

This project explores an approach to trees with snow using a recursive algorithm and includes Three traits: a density layer for the amount of trees and another layer for the amount snow and a third for how strong the branches bend.

Rendering progress indicated on the top left border
Press [s] in live view to download a high resolution png

Artist notes:
Since I moved to Wandlitz, north of Berlin, in the middle of the "Naturpark Barnim" (https://www.barnim-naturpark.de/), in 2003,
I've done a lot of exploring nearby nature. In addition to the beautiful lake and heath landscapes, I fell in love with the wild acacia forests. These strange trees, sometimes more like huge wild grasses, grow so wildly into each other.

I experienced it in all sorts of seasonal change, packed with snow is definitely among the most amazing! 

While playing around with different branching system code snippets, a more and more complex image composition came together. The final script for this project on fx(hash) was finally given more randomness for a wider range of different outputs and an additional random grain filter.

Project link: https://e-art.co/project/schneewald/

Many thanks to jesse (jbird) for the good collaboration, which ultimately made it possible to get this work released.

metadata.name: Shattered Obelisks #41
metadata.description:
Shattered Obelisks began as a work that is dedicated to my habit of mindlessly drawing on paper when I am stressed, depressed or immersed in difficult thoughts.

Like a patient undergoing psychotherapy and piecing together the causes of unconscious fears and anxieties, I and my artwork have assembled ourselves into something shaped, found order in the chaos and separated it from the external noise.

It took 3 months of continuous, obsessive work. I have developed a huge library, designed for hand-like drawing. The functionality of this library is four times larger than what is shown in this drop.

I plan to put this library out into the public domain when I deem it complete, and hope that it will help someone express themselves through the creative process as much as it helped for me.

In case you've encountered a problem with inverted colours, try changing browser or disabling extensions. This problem only occurred once during testing on a massive amount of devices and was resolved by disabling extensions.

IMPORTANT NOTES BLOCK:

NOTE 1: This artwork should be viewed at a browser scale of 100%. Reducing the scale will increase the amount of detail, but may unpredictably affect the preservation of the location of secondary objects.

NOTE 2: This work can be printed on a plotter. Click S for saving it in .SVG.
Detailed instructions and answers to possible questions can be found in the console output of the code.

NOTE 3: This drop is the first one from the series of 3. It will be used as AL ticket in next drops of this series.

@abakshonokoleg
01.08.2022

metadata.name: A24Z #68
metadata.description:
Every artist and collector feels the joy of both creating and collecting. But if I could share the joy of creating with collectors. And collectors with their family and friends, what may be an additive process of joy is now perhaps exponential. Joy to the power of 26 to be exact. 

In this work I invite my friends and collectors to collaborate with me. Though not in coding, but together in a process of creating narratives and visuals. Code and story. We didn‚Äôt use github, just a simple p5.js editor to try out different programs and palettes. Pedrofe and J0rdan pick their palettes tastefully and carefully. okeoke, perhaps more of a genius than he lets on, picks his palettes blind. No hex color picker. Just straight up rhymes.  

In our discussions verbal language was forbidden. Only emojis were allowed to express our tastes and views. Each emojis put down on google doc was taken with absolutely seriousness. 

Pedro: Loves to taking his daily walks on ‚ÄúMagic Mushroom Mountain‚Äù

J0rdan: Wonders about ‚ÄúQuark Question Quiches‚Äù

Okeoke: Just get lost in ‚ÄúFinnegans‚Äô Flower Fields.‚Äù

It has been a great joy to present our illustration book A24Z, 8 more than you know who. Each page expresses the alphabet with the best of our knowledge in semantics and sarcasm. Collect just 1 page, collect the alphabets that spell out your name, collect the whole A to Z. Read it to your children or loved ones. Though you might need to interpolate or extrapolate with great imagination which children all have. But most importantly, like all children, have fun!

Press 1 to save png, only for Chrome, not Safari. Preview images are compressed or broken, test capture at 300 sec.

metadata.name: Chaosplot #106
metadata.description:
Continued exploration of the algorithm from "Chaospill" with a symmetric two tone style that is plotter friendly. The result can be rotated to whatever orientation works best for your display purposes. The code is presented unminified with comments and will be open sourced soon.

Live Mode Controls

Click to regenerate with a different starting seed.
1 - Save a SVG, the result is sized for 11"x17" prints with each color on a separate layer
2 - Save a PNG of the output
3 - Switch paper size to 8.5"x11" letter or A1 for different size plots
4 - Toggle HD mode which increases resolution and disables noise for printing

Code and Outputs are Copyright (C) 2022 Frank Force - Artwork is released under CC BY-NC 4.0.

metadata.name: Gammalt #79
metadata.description:
Celebrating getting old with Fx(hash).

Save as png:
Click ‚Äús‚Äù
or double click/tap

Resolution:
Default image width = 2000px and aspect ratio = 4:3.
Modify the image width between 2000px and 10000px by adding ‚Äú&w=xxxx‚Äù to the url (e.g. &w=4000).
High resolutions are computationally expensive and may take a while.

Background:
The canvas background texture is visible by default. This can be toggled off by adding ‚Äú&b=0‚Äù to the url.
The background scales with resolution to mimic a bigger canvas so it will look different at different resolutions.
At high resolutions a Moir√© pattern may appear on the canvas background texture due to the way images are resized in the browser. It‚Äôs always recommended to download a full resolution version of the piece.
